Date: Sat, 5 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease information, 18 [9],2, 4 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_03.HTM>

Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza In Thailand: Follow-up report No. 47
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Information received on 3 Mar 2005 from Dr Yukol Limlamthong, Director
General, Department of Livestock Development (DLD), Ministry of Agriculture
and Cooperatives, Bangkok:
End of previous report period: 24 Feb 2005 (see Disease Information, 18 [8],
69, dated 25 Feb 2005).
End of this report period: 3 Mar 2005.
Identification of agent: highly pathogenic avian influenza virus subtype H5N1.
Details of new outbreaks:
Province name (number of districts, number of villages).
KamphaengPhet (1,1);
NakhonSawan (1,1);
Nonthaburi (1,1);
Uttaradit (4, 5).
Total: 4 provinces, 7 districts, 8 villages.
Description of affected population in the new outbreaks: native chickens,
cage birds.
[For the number of susceptible, cases and destroyed avians, subscribers are
referred to the original report at the above URL. The totals are:
Outbreaks (villages): 8
Susceptible: 189
Cases: 35
Death: 35
Destroyed: 154
Slaughtered: 0]
Description of affected population in the new outbreaks: native chickens,
cage birds.
Diagnosis:
---------
Laboratories where diagnosis was made: National Institute of Animal Health
and seven Regional Veterinary Research and Development Centers
Diagnostic tests used:
- agar-gel precipitation test;
- haemagglutination test;
- haemagglutination inhibition test;
- pathogen isolation by egg inoculation;
- intracerebral pathogenicity index test.
Results: positive
Control measures undertaken:
- stamping out;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishments.
Treatment of affected animals: no.
Vaccination prohibited: yes.
Other details/comments:
- These outbreaks are part of the highly pathogenic avian influenza epizootic
affecting the country since the re-occurrence of the disease on 3 Jul 2004.
- Since the beginning of Feb 2005, the DLD has been conducting active
surveillance nationwide.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
